events.description: Roman emperor Hadrian adopts Antoninus Pius as his son, effectively making him his successor.
events.html: • 138 – Roman emperor Hadrian adopts Antoninus Pius as his son, effectively making him his successor.[1]

events.description: Khosrow II, the last great Shah of the Sasanian Empire (Iran), is overthrown by his son Kavadh II.
events.html: • 628 – Khosrow II, the last great Shah of the Sasanian Empire (Iran), is overthrown by his son Kavadh II.[2]

events.description: Four thousand defenders of Pilenai commit mass suicide rather than be taken captive by the Teutonic Knights.
events.html: • 1336 – Four thousand defenders of Pilenai commit mass suicide rather than be taken captive by the Teutonic Knights.

events.description: George Frideric Handel's opera Nero premiered in Hamburg.
events.html: • 1705 – George Frideric Handel's opera Nero premiered in Hamburg.[3]

events.description: Samuel Colt is granted a United States patent for his revolver firearm.
events.html: • 1836 – Samuel Colt is granted a United States patent for his revolver firearm.[4]

events.description: Lord George Paulet occupies the Kingdom of Hawaii in the name of Great Britain in the Paulet affair.
events.html: • 1843 – Lord George Paulet occupies the Kingdom of Hawaii in the name of Great Britain in the Paulet affair.[5]

events.description: Hiram Rhodes Revels, a Republican from Mississippi, is sworn into the United States Senate, becoming the first African American ever to sit in Congress.
events.html: • 1870 – Hiram Rhodes Revels, a Republican from Mississippi, is sworn into the United States Senate, becoming the first African American ever to sit in Congress.[6]

events.description: Guangxu Emperor of Qing dynasty China begins his reign, under Empress Dowager Cixi's regency.
events.html: • 1875 – Guangxu Emperor of Qing dynasty China begins his reign, under Empress Dowager Cixi's regency.[7]

events.description: Marie-Adélaïde, the eldest of six daughters of Guillaume IV, becomes the first reigning Grand Duchess of Luxembourg.
events.html: • 1912 – Marie-Adélaïde, the eldest of six daughters of Guillaume IV, becomes the first reigning Grand Duchess of Luxembourg.[8]

entities.name: Guillaume IV, Grand Duke of Luxembourg

events.description: World War I: In the Battle of Verdun, a German unit captures Fort Douaumont, keystone of the French defences, without a fight.
events.html: • 1916 – World War I: In the Battle of Verdun, a German unit captures Fort Douaumont, keystone of the French defences, without a fight.[9]

events.description: World War I: German forces capture Tallinn to virtually complete the occupation of Estonia.
events.html: • 1918 – World War I: German forces capture Tallinn to virtually complete the occupation of Estonia.[10]

entities.name: German occupation of Estonia during World War I

events.description: Georgian capital Tbilisi falls to the invading Russian forces after heavy fighting and the Russians declare the Georgian Soviet Socialist Republic.
events.html: • 1921 – Georgian capital Tbilisi falls to the invading Russian forces after heavy fighting and the Russians declare the Georgian Soviet Socialist Republic.[11]

events.description: Adolf Hitler, having been stateless for seven years, obtains German citizenship when he is appointed a Brunswick state official by Dietrich Klagges, a fellow Nazi. As a result, Hitler is able to run for Reichspräsident in the 1932 election.
events.html: • 1932 – Adolf Hitler, having been stateless for seven years, obtains German citizenship when he is appointed a Brunswick state official by Dietrich Klagges, a fellow Nazi. As a result, Hitler is able to run for Reichspräsident in the 1932 election.[12]

events.description: Launch of the USS Ranger at Newport News, Virginia. It is the first purpose-built aircraft carrier to be commissioned by the US Navy.
events.html: • 1933 – Launch of the USS Ranger at Newport News, Virginia. It is the first purpose-built aircraft carrier to be commissioned by the US Navy.[13]

events.description: As part of British air raid precautions, the first of 2.5 million Anderson shelters is constructed in a garden in Islington, north London.
events.html: • 1939 – As part of British air raid precautions, the first of 2.5 million Anderson shelters is constructed in a garden in Islington, north London.[14]

entities.name: Air Raid Precautions in the United Kingdom

events.description: The outlawed Communist Party of the Netherlands organises a general strike in German-occupied Amsterdam to protest against Nazi persecution of Dutch Jews.
events.html: • 1941 – The outlawed Communist Party of the Netherlands organises a general strike in German-occupied Amsterdam to protest against Nazi persecution of Dutch Jews.[15]

events.description: The formal abolition of Prussia is proclaimed by the Allied Control Council, the Prussian government having already been abolished by the Preußenschlag of 1932.
events.html: • 1947 – The formal abolition of Prussia is proclaimed by the Allied Control Council, the Prussian government having already been abolished by the Preußenschlag of 1932.[16]

events.description: Soviet NKVD forces in Hungary abduct Béla Kovács—secretary-general of the majority Independent Smallholders' Party—and deport him to the USSR in defiance of Parliament. His arrest is an important turning point in the Communist takeover of Hungary.
events.html: • 1947 – Soviet NKVD forces in Hungary abduct Béla Kovács—secretary-general of the majority Independent Smallholders' Party—and deport him to the USSR in defiance of Parliament. His arrest is an important turning point in the Communist takeover of Hungary.[17]

events.description: In a coup d'état led by Klement Gottwald, the Communist Party of Czechoslovakia takes control of government in Prague to end the Third Czechoslovak Republic.
events.html: • 1948 – In a coup d'état led by Klement Gottwald, the Communist Party of Czechoslovakia takes control of government in Prague to end the Third Czechoslovak Republic.[18]

events.description: The first Pan American Games are officially opened in Buenos Aires by Argentine President Juan Perón.
events.html: • 1951 – The first Pan American Games are officially opened in Buenos Aires by Argentine President Juan Perón.[19]

events.description: In his speech On the Cult of Personality and Its Consequences, Nikita Khrushchev, leader of the Soviet Union, denounces Stalin.
events.html: • 1956 – In his speech On the Cult of Personality and Its Consequences, Nikita Khrushchev, leader of the Soviet Union, denounces Stalin.[20]

entities.name: On the Cult of Personality and Its Consequences

events.description: The government of Suriname is overthrown by a military coup led by Dési Bouterse.
events.html: • 1980 – The government of Suriname is overthrown by a military coup led by Dési Bouterse.[21]

events.description: People Power Revolution: President of the Philippines Ferdinand Marcos flees the nation after 20 years of rule; Corazon Aquino becomes the Philippines' first female president.
events.html: • 1986 – People Power Revolution: President of the Philippines Ferdinand Marcos flees the nation after 20 years of rule; Corazon Aquino becomes the Philippines' first female president.[22]

events.description: Disbandment of the Warsaw Pact at a meeting of its members in Budapest.
events.html: • 1991 – Disbandment of the Warsaw Pact at a meeting of its members in Budapest.[23]

events.description: American-Israeli extremist Baruch Goldstein commits a mass shooting at the Cave of the Patriarchs mausoleum, leaving 29 dead and over 100 injured before he was disarmed and beaten to death by survivors.
events.html: • 1994 – American-Israeli extremist Baruch Goldstein commits a mass shooting at the Cave of the Patriarchs mausoleum, leaving 29 dead and over 100 injured before he was disarmed and beaten to death by survivors.[24]

events.description: Alitalia Flight 1553 crashes at Genoa Cristoforo Colombo Airport in Genoa, Italy, killing four.
events.html: • 1999 – Alitalia Flight 1553 crashes at Genoa Cristoforo Colombo Airport in Genoa, Italy, killing four.[25]

events.description: Soldiers of the Bangladesh Rifles mutiny at their headquarters in Pilkhana, Dhaka, Bangladesh, resulting in 74 deaths, including 57 army officials.
events.html: • 2009 – Soldiers of the Bangladesh Rifles mutiny at their headquarters in Pilkhana, Dhaka, Bangladesh, resulting in 74 deaths, including 57 army officials.[26]

events.description: Turkish Airlines Flight 1951 crashed during landing at the Amsterdam Schiphol Airport, Netherlands, primarily due to a faulty radio altimeter, resulting in the death of nine passengers and crew including all three pilots.
events.html: • 2009 – Turkish Airlines Flight 1951 crashed during landing at the Amsterdam Schiphol Airport, Netherlands, primarily due to a faulty radio altimeter, resulting in the death of nine passengers and crew including all three pilots.[27]

events.description: At least 310 people are killed in avalanches in northeastern Afghanistan.
events.html: • 2015 – At least 310 people are killed in avalanches in northeastern Afghanistan.[28]

events.description: Three people are killed and fourteen others injured in a series of shootings in the small Kansas cities of Newton and Hesston.
events.html: • 2016 – Three people are killed and fourteen others injured in a series of shootings in the small Kansas cities of Newton and Hesston.[29]
